Describe how surface body ECG is generated. 

The heart sends electrical impulses around the body which can be detected on the surface of the skin. Leads are placed in different positions on the body and receive slightly different readings due to variations in relative position to the heart. 

 

Briefly describe the electrical processes of the heart that are reflected in the ECG, and relate these to the cardiac cycle.  

-SA node produces P wave causing atrial contraction as the action potential passes through atria to the AV node 

-AV node propagates action potential through AV bundle then left and right bundles, which moves through the intraventricular septum to cause septal depolarisation seen as the Q wave.  

-Ventricles depolarise, seen early and late as R and S waves respectively 

-Ventricles repolarise, seen as the T wave 

 

Compare the functional characteristics of cardiac, skeletal and smooth muscle 

-Skeletal muscle: striated, are long, have multiple nuclei due to the fusion of myoblasts, and are not electrically connected and must rather be activated synaptically 

-Cardiac muscle: striated, irregularly branched shape, have single nuclei, are electrically-connected via gap junctions, possess automaticity 

-Smooth muscle: no striation, irregular attachment sites of myofilaments, have single nuclei, poorly developed ER, from autonomic sympathetic and parasympathetic, synaptically 

 

Briefly describe the function of actin, myosin, tropomyosin and troponin, relating molecular structure to function in the contractile apparatus 

 

-Actin: Protein composed of F-actin double strand, tropomyosin wrapped around the F-actin, and troponin complexes on the surface of the tropomyosin, attached to Z-disk on one end whilst free on the other 

-Myosin: Made up of many strands (made of two heavy chains) which have two myosin heads (light chains), acting as cross-bridges attaching the myosin to the actin 

-Tropomyosin: wrapped helically around the F-actin, attached to it by troponin 

-Troponin complex: Shields active sites on F-actin from binding with myosin heads 

 

Role of Ca2+ in skeletal vs smooth muscle 

In skeletal muscle, the introduction of Ca2+ will cause the binding of troponin. This un-shields the active sties on F-actin, allowing binding to myosin heads and the steps shown in the picture below. Levels of intracellular Ca2+ serve as a regulatory mechanism. 

 

In smooth muscle, there is no troponin mechanism. Instead, contraction is mediated by Ca2+ regulated phosphorylation of myosin.  

 

Briefly describe the steps in excitation-contraction coupling 

Briefly describe the role of extracellular and intracellular calcium in the contraction of cardiac muscle and control of heart rate 

In skeletal myocytes, an action potential causes the activation of dihydropyrodine receptors (DHP receptor), causing the activation of Ryanodine receptors, and then the release of Ca2+ from the sarcoplasmic reticulum leading to contraction. 

 

In cardiac myocytes, extracellular Ca2+ ions enter inside cardiac myocytes via voltage-sensitive calcium channels during the plateau phase of the action potential. The increase in intracellular Ca2+ activates the Ryanodine receptors, causing the sarcoplasmic reticulum to release Ca2+ hence leading to contraction.  

 

Briefly describe the sodium/potassium ATPase 

This pumps Na+ and K+ against their concentration gradients by using ATP, pumping out 3 Na+ for every 2 K+ pumped in. This is inhibited by cardiac glycosides eg digoxin, ouabain. 

 

NCX Na+/Ca2+ exchanger: 

This pumps Ca2+ out of the cell against its concentration gradient by using Na+ electrochemical gradient. 1 Ca2+ is exchanged for 3 Na+. No ATP is required. Note that this pump may directly lead on from the actions of the Sodium/Potassium ATPase.  

 

Briefly describe the role of ATP in contraction and relaxation of cardiac muscle and maintenance of ionic gradients. 

-ATP used in cocking and usage of myosin head to move along actin 

-ATP used to pump Ca2+ back into sarcoplasmic reticulum for relaxation of muscle 

-ATP used to maintain Na+ and K+ concentration gradients for future action potential 

 

Briefly describe how ANS receptors interact with ion channel function 

-An increase in cardiac sympathetic activity due to the release of adrenaline across a synaptic cleft from a sympathetic nerve activates Beta-1 Adrenoreceptors, which leads to an increase in intracellular Ca2+ and thus harder contractions. 

-Beta-blockers act as antagonists on these receptors, causing a decrease in Ca2+ flowing into the cell.  

 

Note: A Ryanodine-receptor blocker can also decrease contractility.
